I explored the code by searching `internal/` for `Publish(` and `Subscribe(` first, then read the event bus and each module file: `internal/event/bus.go`, `internal/bag/bag.go`, `internal/task/task.go`, `internal/achievement/achievement.go`, `internal/equipment/equipment.go`, `internal/signin/signin.go`, `internal/mail/mail.go`, and `internal/server/server.go`. I also searched for `ClaimReward`, `ClaimAttachment`, `AddTask`, and `AddAchievement` to trace initialization and command wiring.

Runtime verification matched most of the code paths. `checkin day 1` produced `signin.claimed` and immediately sent mail. Claiming that mail only logged `[Mail] claimed attachment...`; bag stayed empty and tasks did not move, confirming the broken `mail.claimed` path. Direct `additem 2001` advanced task `3001`, completed it, unlocked achievement `4001`, and sent achievement mail. Adding `2002` twice completed task `3002`, unlocked `4002`, and also unlocked `4003`, which matches the faulty collector implementation. Adding `3001` and `3002` auto-equipped weapon and armor and then unlocked `4004`. Finally, `claimreward day 2` succeeded even though day 2 had not been checked in; it only logged `day 2 reward claimed again`, changed no mail, and left sign-in state unchanged, confirming both the missing guard and the orphan `signin.reward` event.

The main anomaly is that several published events are dead ends: `mail.claimed`, `signin.reward`, `item.removed`, and `mail.sent` have no consumers. Two of those are user-visible defects because exposed commands depend on them.
